BSDC FRONTEND V2 — PERCEPTION LAYER SPEC

This file defines VISUAL EXPERIENCE PRIORITY.

It overrides all layout and structural decisions when perception conflicts exist.

---

# 1. CORE PRINCIPLE

The system is NOT defined by layout.

The system is defined by:

> what the user’s eye is forced to perceive as dominant at any moment.

---

# 2. VISUAL DOMINANCE RULE (CRITICAL)

At any scroll position:

ONLY ONE PRIMARY DOMINANT OBJECT may exist.

Everything else MUST behave as background perception noise.

---

# 3. DOMINANCE HIERARCHY

Each node must enforce this hierarchy:

## Tier 1 — PRIMARY MASS (Hero / Active Focus)
- occupies visual gravity center
- largest scale influence
- highest contrast
- sharpest clarity
- slowest motion

## Tier 2 — SECONDARY STRUCTURE
- supports composition
- visible but non-dominant
- medium contrast
- partial blur or reduced opacity
- moderate motion

## Tier 3 — PERIPHERAL FIELD
- background geometry
- environmental context only
- low opacity (5–20%)
- no readable UI importance

---

# 4. CONTRAST RULE (NO FLATNESS)

Flatness = equal visual weight distribution.

Forbidden state:

- multiple elements same contrast
- uniform opacity
- uniform scale distribution

Required state:

- strong contrast separation between layers
- clear focal point at all times

---

# 5. “ALIVENESS” DEFINITION

A node is considered ALIVE ONLY IF:

- it has internal visual tension (asymmetry or imbalance)
- it has depth separation (foreground vs background conflict)
- it has at least one non-centered dominant element
- it reacts subtly to cursor without becoming UI-driven

If none of the above exist → node is DEAD FLAT.

---

# 6. FOCAL LOCK SYSTEM

At any scroll state:

- ONE node is FOCUSED
- ONE node is TRANSITIONING
- ALL others are PERIPHERAL

This is mandatory.

No equal visibility allowed.

---

# 7. NODE EXPERIENCE RULE

Each node must feel like:

NOT:
- section
- screen
- component

BUT:
- physical space with internal gravity

---

# 8. TYPOGRAPHY PERCEPTION RULE

Text is NOT UI.

Text is MASS.

Rules:
- headlines must behave like physical objects
- must create directional force in composition
- must never be centered by default unless intentional equilibrium is needed
- must dominate local visual hierarchy

---

# 9. MOTION PERCEPTION RULE

Motion is NOT animation.

Motion is:

- shift of attention
- redistribution of visual weight
- rebalancing of depth field

No motion may exist without perceptual consequence.

---

# 10. VALIDATION CHECK

Before output is accepted:

Check:

- Is there a clear visual dominant object?
- Is there hierarchy between layers?
- Does anything feel flat or equally weighted?

If YES → INVALID RENDER

---

# 11. SUCCESS CRITERIA

System is correct ONLY if:

- user eye always lands on one dominant structure
- background feels like environment, not UI
- nodes feel physically different in weight
- scrolling changes “attention gravity”, not layout

END SPEC